{"parse":{"title":"Crux (literary)","pageid":8077495,"revid":810714186,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p><b>Crux</b> (<a href=\"/wiki/Latin\" title=\"Latin\">Latin</a> for \"cross\", \"gallow\", or \"t-shape\") is a term applied by <a href=\"/wiki/Palaeography\" title=\"Palaeography\">palaeographers</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Textual_criticism\" title=\"Textual criticism\">textual critics</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Bibliography\" title=\"Bibliography\">bibliographers</a>, and literary scholars to a point of significant corruption in a literary text. More serious than a simple slip of the pen or typographical error, a crux (probably deriving from Latin <i>crux interpretum</i> = \"cross of the interpreters\") is difficult or impossible to interpret and resolve. Cruxes occur in a wide range of pre-modern (<a href=\"/wiki/Ancient_history\" title=\"Ancient history\">ancient</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Middle_Ages\" title=\"Middle Ages\">medieval</a>, and <a href=\"/wiki/Renaissance\" title=\"Renaissance\">Renaissance</a>) texts, printed and manuscript.\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Shakespearean_examples\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Shakespearean examples</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Typographic_conventions\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Typographic conventions</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#Notes\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Notes</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Shakespearean_examples\">Shakespearean examples</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Crux_(literary)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Shakespearean examples\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Though widely exposed to readers and scholars, the texts of <a href=\"/wiki/William_Shakespeare\" title=\"William Shakespeare\">William Shakespeare</a>'s plays yield some of the most famous literary cruxes. Some have been resolved fairly well. In <a href=\"/wiki/Henry_V_(play)\" title=\"Henry V (play)\"><i>Henry V,</i></a> II.iii.16-7, the <a href=\"/wiki/First_Folio\" title=\"First Folio\">First Folio</a> text has the Hostess describe <a href=\"/wiki/Falstaff\" title=\"Falstaff\">Falstaff</a> on his death-bed like this:\n</p>\n<style data-mw-deduplicate=\"TemplateStyles:r856303468\">.mw-parser-output .templatequote{overflow:hidden;margin:1em 0;padding:0 40px}.mw-parser-output .templatequote .templatequotecite{line-height:1.5em;text-align:left;padding-left:1.6em;margin-top:0}</style><blockquote class=\"templatequote\"><p>...his nose was sharp as a pen, and 'a Table of green fields.\n</p></blockquote>\n<p><a href=\"/wiki/Lewis_Theobald\" title=\"Lewis Theobald\">Lewis Theobald</a>'s editorial correction, \"and 'a [he] babbl'd of green fields\", has won almost universal acceptance from subsequent editors.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> Similarly, the \"dram of eale\" In <i><a href=\"/wiki/Hamlet\" title=\"Hamlet\">Hamlet</a></i> I, iv, 36 can be sensibly interpreted as \"dram of ev'l [evil].\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Other Shakespearean cruxes have not been so successfully resolved. In <i><a href=\"/wiki/All%27s_Well_That_Ends_Well\" title=\"All&#39;s Well That Ends Well\">All's Well That Ends Well</a>,</i> IV.ii,38-9, Diana observes to Bertram,\n</p>\n<link rel=\"mw-deduplicated-inline-style\" href=\"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r856303468\"/><blockquote class=\"templatequote\"><div class=\"poem\">\n<p>I see that men make ropes in such a scarre,<br />\nThat we'll forsake ourselves.\n</p>\n</div>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Editors have reached no consensus on exactly what \"ropes in such a scarre\" can mean, or how it should be amended: \"no satisfactory explanation or emendation has been offered.\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> Perhaps the best alternative that has been proposed is \"may rope 's [us] in such a snare.\" Another unresolved Shakespearean crux is the \"runaway's eyes\" in <i><a href=\"/wiki/Romeo_and_Juliet\" title=\"Romeo and Juliet\">Romeo and Juliet</a>,</i> III, ii, 6.<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Sometimes a crux will not require emendation, but simply present a knotty problem of comprehension. In <i><a href=\"/wiki/Henry_IV,_Part_1\" title=\"Henry IV, Part 1\">Henry IV, Part 1</a>,</i> IV, i, 98-9, Sir Richard Vernon describes Prince Hal and his comrades as appearing:\n</p>\n<link rel=\"mw-deduplicated-inline-style\" href=\"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r856303468\"/><blockquote class=\"templatequote\"><div class=\"poem\">\n<p>All plum'd like estridges, that with the wind<br />\nbated like eagles having lately bath'd...\n</p>\n</div>\n</blockquote>\n<p>This is most likely a reference to some obscure assertion about animal behavior, and has sent researchers poring through dusty volumes in search of an explanation.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Typographic_conventions\">Typographic conventions</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Crux_(literary)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Typographic conventions\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>In editions of Greek and Roman authors, a crux is marked off by <a href=\"/wiki/Dagger_(typography)\" title=\"Dagger (typography)\">obeli</a>, to indicate that the editor is not confident enough either to follow the manuscript reading or to print a conjecture.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Notes\">Notes</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Crux_(literary)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: Notes\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Blakemore Evans, <i>Riverside Shakespeare,</i> pp. 945, 973.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Blakemore Evans, pp. 1148, 1188.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Blakemore Evans, pp. 530, 543.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-4\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Blakemore Evans, p. 1077.</span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Crux_(literary)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li>Evans, G. Blakemore, textual editor. <i>The Riverside Shakespeare.</i> Boston, Houghton Mifflin, 1974.</li>\n<li>Harlow, C. G. \"Shakespeare, Nashe, and the Ostridge Crux in <i>1 Henry IV.</i>\" <i>Shakespeare Quarterly</i> Vol. 17, No. 2 (Spring 1966), pp.&#160;171\u20134.</li>\n<li>Newcomer, Alphonso Gerald. \"A Shakespeare Crux.\" <i>Modern Philology,</i> Vol. 11, No. 1 (July 1913), pp.&#160;141\u20134.</li></ul>\n\n<!-- \nNewPP limit report\nParsed by mw1344\nCached time: 20180901153050\nCache expiry: 1900800\nDynamic content: false\nCPU time usage: 0.048 seconds\nReal time usage: 0.059 seconds\nPreprocessor visited node count: 254/1000000\nPreprocessor generated node count: 0/1500000\nPost\u2010expand include size: 727/2097152 bytes\nTemplate argument size: 204/2097152 bytes\nHighest expansion depth: 7/40\nExpensive parser function count: 0/500\nUnstrip recursion depth: 1/20\nUnstrip post\u2010expand size: 2271/5000000 bytes\nNumber of Wikibase entities loaded: 0/400\nLua time usage: 0.004/10.000 seconds\nLua memory usage: 525 KB/50 MB\n-->\n<!--\nTransclusion expansion time report (%,ms,calls,template)\n100.00%   45.904      1 -total\n 56.90%   26.120      1 Template:Reflist\n 34.47%   15.822      3 Template:Quote\n  4.28%    1.966      1 Template:Main_other\n-->\n\n<!-- Saved in parser cache with key enwiki:pcache:idhash:8077495-0!canonical and timestamp 20180901153050 and revision id 810714186\n -->\n</div>"},"langlinks":[],"categories":[{"sortkey":"","*":"Palaeography"},{"sortkey":"","*":"Bibliography"}],"links":[{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"All's Well That Ends Well"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Ancient history"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Bibliography"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Dagger (typography)"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Falstaff"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"First Folio"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Hamlet"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Henry IV, Part 1"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Henry V (play)"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Latin"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Lewis Theobald"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Middle Ages"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Palaeography"},{"ns":0,"exists":